# Covid19_economy_analysis


<div id="use-case" class="section level2 unnumbered">
<h2 class="unnumbered">Use Case</h2>
<p>Our app analyzes how COVID-19 positive cases impacted the U.S. economy, focusing on indicators such as consumer spending, open small business, and employment. The aim of the app is to discover how the number of positive COVID-19 cases influenced consumer spending across industries, as well as revealing how COVID-19 positive cases impacted small businesses or changes in employment.</p>
<p>Our target audience for this app is for federal and state level policy advisers and analysts. By incorporating a variety of data sources and joining them together to display in an interactive dashboard, our goal is to allow those policy advisers to quickly interpret how COVID-19 has impacted various aspects of the economy on a state by state level. With our app, the user can answer questions such as:</p>
<ul>
<li>For consumer spending, which industries on average declined the most during the past year? Which industries had the steepest drop? Which industry was affected the least?</li>
<li>Does there appear to be a relationship between the stimulus checks and consumer spending?</li>
<li>How did stimulus check help small businesses, consumer spending and employment, and how effective was it?</li>
<li>Is there a correlation between percent changes in COVID-19 cases and small businesses’ open/revenue?</li>
</ul>

</div>

<div id="data-source-and-structure" class="section level2 unnumbered">
<h2 class="unnumbered">Data Source and Structure</h2>
<p>The primary data sources are from Opportunity Insights’ Economic Tracker, a public database which compiled data from various sources on consumer spending, open small businesses, employment. We then build upon these with additional relevant datasets to supplement for exploratory data analysis and statistical analysis.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Consumer Spending</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Original Source: <a href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/OpportunityInsights/EconomicTracker/main/data/Affinity%20-%20State%20-%20Daily.csv">Affinity Solutions</a></li>
</ul>
<p>Consumer spending is measured via aggregated and anonymized data on credit &amp; debit card spending collected by Affinity, which is a company that aggregates that information - the company captures nearly 10% of credit and debit card spending in the US.</p>
<p>The data seasonally adjusted credit &amp; debit card spending relative to January 2020 and is daily (presented as a 7-day moving average). The data is broken down by industries (merchant codes used by Affinity Solutions) and income based on consumer zip code (the transactions are linked to zip codes where the consumer lives and those zip codes are classified into income categories based on median household income from the American Community Survey)</p>
<p>Number of Observations: 21713</p>
<p>Date range: January 22, 2020 to April 4, 2021</p>
<p>Industries:</p>
<ul>
<li>Accommodation, Food Service</li>
<li>Arts, Entertainment, Recreation</li>
<li>All Merchant Category</li>
<li>General Merchant, Apparel, Accessories</li>
<li>Grocery</li>
<li>Healthcare, Social Assistant</li>
<li>Transportation, Warehousing</li>
<li>Retail with Grocery</li>
<li>Retail without Grocery</li>
</ul>
<p>Income:</p>
<ul>
<li>High Median Income (median household income &gt;$78,000)</li>
<li>Middle Median Income (median household income $46,000-78,000)</li>
<li>Low Median Income (median household income &lt;$46,000)</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr />
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Small Business Open</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Original Source: <a href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/OpportunityInsights/EconomicTracker/main/data/Womply%20-%20State%20-%20Daily.csv">Womply</a></li>
</ul>
<p>Small businesses that are open are defined by those having financial transaction activity. This data originates from Womply, a company that aggregates data from credit card processors.</p>
<p>The number of small businesses open is defined by having had at least one transactions in the last 3 days and is daily (presented as a 7-day moving average). The data is broken down by industry (as defined by NAICS supersector) and and income is based on business zip code (the transactions are linked to zip codes where the business is located and those zip codes are classified into income categories based on median household income from the American Community Survey).</p>
<p>Number of Observations: 22434</p>
<p>Date range: January 22, 2020 to April 14, 2021</p>
<p>Industries:</p>
<ul>
<li>Education, Health Services Revenue</li>
<li>Education, Health Services Open</li>
<li>Leisure, Hospitality Revenue</li>
<li>Leisure, Hospitality Open</li>
<li>Professional, Business Services Revenue</li>
<li>Professional, Business Services Open</li>
<li>Retail, Transportation Revenue</li>
<li>Retail, Transportation Open</li>
<li>All Revenue</li>
<li>All Open</li>
</ul>
<p>Income:</p>
<ul>
<li>High Income (median household income &gt;$78,000)</li>
<li>Middle Income (median household income $46,000-78,000)</li>
<li>Low Income (median household income &lt;$46,000)</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr />
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Employment</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Original Source: <a href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/OpportunityInsights/EconomicTracker/main/data/Employment%20-%20State%20-%20Daily.csv">Paychex, Intuit, Earnin, Kronos</a></li>
</ul>
<p>The employment data is combined via several data sources. Employment measures the changes in employment rates based on payroll data from Paychex and Intuit, worker-level data on employment and earnings from Earnin, and timesheet data from Kronos.</p>
<p>The data counts the number of active employees and is daily (presented as a 7-day moving average). The data is broken down by industries and wage levels.</p>
<p>Number of Observations: 19788</p>
<p>Date range: January 22, 2020 to February 12, 2021</p>
<p>Industries:</p>
<ul>
<li>Education, Health Services</li>
<li>Leisure, Hospitality</li>
<li>Professional, Business Services</li>
<li>Retail, Transportation</li>
</ul>
<p>Wages:</p>
<ul>
<li>High Income (&gt;$60,000)</li>
<li>Middle Income ($27,000-60,000)</li>
<li>Low Income (&lt;$27,000)</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr />
<p>We use additional data to join with the primary datasets (Consumer Spending, Small Business Open, Employment). Each of the 3 datasets also include data on the following:</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>COVID-19</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Original Source: <a href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/OpportunityInsights/EconomicTracker/main/data/COVID%20-%20State%20-%20Daily.csv">Centers for Disease Control and Prevention</a></li>
</ul>
<p>COVID-19 data consists of the number of cases and deaths daily (presented as a 7-day moving average) by state. The COVID-19 data is joined by the date and statefips. Each observation includes a count of COVID-19 cases and death as new confirmed COVID-19 cases/deaths per 100,000 people, presented as a 7-day moving average.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>GeoIDs - State</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Original Source: <a href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/OpportunityInsights/EconomicTracker/main/data/GeoIDs%20-%20State.csv">Opportunity Insights</a></li>
</ul>
<p>The GeoID data uses ‘statefips’ as the geographic identifier in which we joined with the primary datasets. The GeoID data provides the state name, 2-letter state abbreviation, and the state population in 2019 from Census Bureau estimates.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>State Lockdown</strong></p>
<p>The State Lockdown data includes information on how many days in lockdown each state has been under. This data uses ‘statefips’ as the geographic identifier, and includes the dates when the lockdown started/ended.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr />
</div>
